=========================================================
CONCURRENCY vs PARALLELISM (C++ INTERVIEW NOTES)
=========================================================

Definition
----------

Concurrency:
Multiple tasks make progress during the same time period.
The CPU switches between tasks (interleaving execution).

Parallelism:
Multiple tasks execute at the exact same time using multiple CPU cores.

---------------------------------------------------------

Key Differences

| Concurrency | Parallelism |
|-------------|-------------|
| Multiple tasks progress together | Multiple tasks execute simultaneously |
| May use a single CPU core | Requires multiple CPU cores |
| Achieved by context switching | Achieved by running on different cores |
| Improves responsiveness | Improves performance |

---------------------------------------------------------

Example

Concurrency (Single Core)

CPU

Task A
 ↓
Task B
 ↓
Task A
 ↓
Task B

(The CPU rapidly switches between tasks.)

---------------------------------------------------------

Parallelism (Multi Core)

Core 1              Core 2

Task A            Task B

(Both execute simultaneously.)

---------------------------------------------------------

Real-world Examples

Concurrency

✓ Web browser
- UI thread
- Download thread
- Rendering thread

(OS switches between threads on a single core.)

Parallelism

✓ Image processing
✓ Video encoding
✓ Matrix multiplication

(Work is divided across multiple CPU cores.)

---------------------------------------------------------

Interview Points

✓ Concurrency is about managing multiple tasks.
✓ Parallelism is about executing multiple tasks simultaneously.
✓ Parallelism is a type of concurrency.
✓ Modern multicore systems often use both.

---------------------------------------------------------

One-line Interview Answer

"Concurrency means multiple tasks make progress together by interleaving execution, while parallelism means multiple tasks execute at the same time on different CPU cores."
